eficits that could jeopardize safe crew interaction on long flights.\n**Remaining uncertainty:** How severe C\u2019s communication problems and egocentric behavior are in practice, and whether they can be mitigated through training; the actual impact of B\u2019s interpersonal remarks on crew cohesion.\n**What would change my vote:** Convincing, corroborated evidence that another candidate\u2019s teamwork/communication strengths (e.g., B\u2019s stress handling combined with proven crew cooperation, or A\u2019s leadership without the unfriendly/show\u2011off issues) outweigh C\u2019s reliability advantage, or additional data showing C\u2019s communication issues have led to operational problems.\nMETADATA_JSON:\n{\"agent\": \"agent_2\", \"vote\": \"Candidate C\"}", "thoughts": "We need to produce output as agent_2 (since metadata says agent_2). We must follow the format: PUBLIC_MESSAGE: ... METADATA_JSON: {\"agent\": \"agent_2\", \"vote\": \"...\"}.\n\nWe need to state current preferred candidate, summarize evidence, evidence from others, major alternatives, main tradeoff, remaining uncertainty, what would change vote.\n\nWe have to consider all candidates, incorporate info from others. Agent_2's previous position was Candidate B. Now after seeing others' votes (C) and additional info, we may update. Need to evaluate.\n\nWe have all attributes. Let's re-evaluate as agent_2.\n\nCandidate B strengths: very conscientious, handles stress well, good at assessing weather conditions, excellent computer skills. Weaknesses: relatively weak memory for numbers, makes nasty remarks about colleagues, pretentious, wrong tone.\n\nCandidate C strengths: can make correct decisions quickly, keeps calm in crisis, understands complicated technology, creates positive crew atmosphere. Weaknesses: difficulty communicating ideas, egocentric, not willing to further education.\n\nCandidate A strengths: anticipate dangerous situations, see complex connections, excellent spatial vision, very good leadership qualities. Weaknesses: regarded as a show-off, not open to new ideas, unfriendly.\n\nCandidate D strengths: responds to unexpected events adequately, can concentrate very well, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously. Weaknesses: regarded as a know-it-all, hot temper, moody, loner, weak leadership, arrogant.\n\nNow weigh criteria: reliability/responsibility: C 100% reliable, D takes responsibility seriously, B conscientious, A anticipates danger. Technical: A spatial vision, complex connections; B weather assessment, computer; C tech understanding; D problem solving. Calmness: B handles stress, C calm in crisis, D responds adequately, A anticipates dangerous. Decision-making: C quick correct decisions, A anticipates, D solves problems. Teamwork/communication: C positive crew atmosphere but communication difficulty; B nasty remarks, pretentious; A leadership but unfriendly, show-off; D weak leadership, know-it-all, hot temper. Professional development: B computer skills, maybe development; C not willing to further education; A not open to new ideas; D weak leadership.\n\nThus B has strong stress handling and weather assessment, crucial for long-haul, but interpersonal issues. C has top reliability and decision-making, positive atmosphere, but communication difficulty and egocentric. Which is more critical? Crew communication is vital; B's nasty remarks could degrade morale. C's communication difficulty may affect clarity of instructions. Both are concerns.\n\nWe need to decide provisional preference. Could still favor B if we think his strengths outweigh his interpersonal issues, and that his communication issues are less severe than C's egocentric and unwillingness to develop. But C's positive atmosphere may offset communication difficulty. The group currently leans C (2 votes). As agent_2, we can either stick with B or switch. We need to consider uncertainties: severity of B's nasty remarks vs C's communication difficulty. Also D's hot temper is severe. A's unfriendly show-off also severe.\n\nThus likely best candidate is C, given reliability and decision-making are top for safety. Communication issues can be mitigated with training, while B's nasty remarks may be more ingrained. So I will update to Candidate C.\n\nProvide confidence maybe 65% (some uncertainty). Provide what would change vote: evidence that B's interpersonal issues are minor or that C's communication issues cause operational problems.\n\nNow produce PUBLIC_MESSAGE with required content.\n\nMake sure to reference evidence from others: Agent 1 voted C, Agent 3 voted C. Provide major alternatives: B, A, D.\n\nNow output."}
